description.text:
This is more of a love letter to my favorite wargame than anything. So, this is easy. It's basically EVERYTIHNG you might need for warmachine. Flags, Templates, Proxy bases, health gauges, blast keys, objective areas, Front/Back arc paint jig, The works!

My objective here is that you will NOT need another template set if you build this one. An optional idea is to cut in acrylics since a lot of this works best if you can write over it with a dry-erase marker (like the objective HP boxes).

So... Why beta? Mainly because I'm releasing it as that so that people can criticize it and suggest some ideas. So, Fire away!

Note: The Blast template has a sort of strange option you might like: Basically, it's the measurement ruler that looks like a dented line. You mount that below the template cut in acrylic, and use the cut brackets and either some glue between the brackets (with care that the disc can move along the line's channel) or a nut and bolt. This allows you to use a blast template that you can measure deviation in one swift move. Try it!

Remember, a tip is always appreciated. A comment and a photo is appreciated as well!

Notes:

The Echo Dot V2 fits perfectly when I print it with PLA, I haven't tried anything else but note that a perfect fit may require a small amount of rescaling with other filaments.

Takes about 4 to 5 hours to print at 80mm/s. Dimensions work well with PLA but the fit will probably be little tight with ABS so you may need to scale it to 1.1% or so.

The circular slot on the bottom is for a strand of Ninjaflex filament that will keep it from sliding on slick surfaces, simply insert a piece of Ninjaflex into the slot after printing... this, of course, is optional but it's there if you need it.

The hole through the bottom is there to help you remove the Dot from the Stand when the fit is extremely tight... just push the Dot free with the eraser side of a pencil.

I used Simplify3D to slice and print this model.

title: Sample spool, remixed for the Malyan 180 and similar clones

description.text:
Based off Wodllod's spool, this has been remixed to work better with the Malyan 180 (and other clones of similar design.) This version doesn't require a bearing, and instead can be put snug against the spool bracers that came with the m180. The arms were also made smaller and more narrow, as I had a bit of trouble with Wodllod's version where the arms would get caught on the bars that the spool pins are attached to, and because I had some more tightly wound filament samples than would fit his design.

You can use the arms from Wodllod's version with the base of this remix, and the arms from this remix with Wodllod's version.

You will need:
1x Spool Base
3x Spool Arm
3x Screws and matching nuts (I used 4-40x1/2s because I had them. The holes are 4mm in diameter so M3 and in theory M4 should work)

Edit: Added a longer arm that I use with PushPlastics loose coils.

description.text: After a few experiments and discussions, I finally settled on this design for tidying up cable mess. Two models are provided to allow you use standard printer filament (either 1.75mm or 3mm - both models are provided) to tie everything together.

Once you've printed however many parts you need for the length of tidy you want to create, take a length of filament (or string, elastic, electrical wire ... anything really that will fit neatly and can be tied off) and begin stringing on to the filament alternately cable chain part, then separator. Once you've cable all your chain parts used up, take a second piece of filament and begin to string through the cable parts on your chain already and add a separator between each.

Now you have every thing on the filament (and this is where you'll have to adapt if you're not using printer filament), cut the filament at one end and use a lighter (or other heating device you have to hand) to deform the end of the filament. With the filament slightly molten, use a pair of pliers of knife or spatula to push on the end of the filament to spread it slightly. Do this with both filament trails at one end, then pull through the filament at the other end of the chain to get the chain straight and the filament taut. Repeat the process to melt and deform this end. You're now done and should have a complete chain. You're now ready to string your cables through.

The design given has a 2mm thick edge, with holes of 2.6mm (to take 1.75mm filament comfortably) and 3.85mm (to take 3mm filament). The cable chain part provides a gap of 40mm width and 20mm depth. This is then sized to be 20mm high. The separators are 15mm high.

Maybe this is not quite what you want, in which case, feel free to copy the design using OnShape and customize it to your needs.

description.text:
I have to give some mad props to Rebizov who totally inspired me. I have a 3-year-old son (youngest of 4) who got a Duplo Batman set that has a cannon. It comes with yellow arrows but I thought "How cool would it be if Batman had an arsenal of different-colored arrows?" My 3-year-old agreed the idea would be great.

I found Rebizov's Duplo arrow which fit the bill. We love it! The only thing I noticed was that I had some difficulty with the bullet working in the cannon off the print plate. I had to shave the shaft with a Dremel in order for it to be able to be loaded - it was just a little too thick. Yes, perhaps it was due to my printer or perhaps due to some variation in the cannons through time? Then, I had the issue of the shaft breaking off the bowl - it consistently broke right at the layer where the "plus" of the shaft meets the "plus" that connects it to the bowl after some use. Friction welding worked but I thought I might try and fix both issues for my own purposes.

So, here we are, a new Duplo-compatible arrow designed from scratch in 123D Design. I used calipers to match the bowl's dimensions a touch more precisely (the bowl is not simply a sphere cut in half but just a bit below the "equator"), added some optional support material built-in to help with tricky overhangs, thinned out the shaft, and added a thick area around the shaft where it joins to the bowl to help reduce the chance of breakage.

It works great for me and I hope it works well for you!

Notes:

I've included various versions of this with differing amounts of supports to meet your needs. If you wish to use your slicer's support material, that's great! Otherwise, I have two other versions with two patterns of support material. I prefer the one with the right angles over the grid as it is easier to remove. In all versions, however, I left in the support material for the hooks which click into the latch system in the Duplo cannon.

I prefer to not use a fan when printing this. I found the cooling of the fan could cause some of the thin layers to warp - slow cooling helped alleviate that.

I print in PLA. I suspect that you might have different results with ABS and would suggest experimenting some if you choose to use that.

I use the Cura slicer when slicing the model. For some reason, the path taken when using Slic3r resulted in the shaft curling at the extremes of the "plus" shape, making it impossible to insert into the cannon. Cura left nice, clean edges.
There isn't much to do after printing other than remove support material. The supports on the shaft for the hooks should remove cleanly with pliers. Sand the bowl if you desire.

I used digital calipers on a Duplo arrow, lots of measurements, and 123D Design to assemble the model.

I found a great way of making my models in 123D Design that allows for modifications in the future should I need them. Binary operations in 123D Design cannot be split in a file that has been saved, then loaded at another time. (Binary operations are "Merge" and "Subtract".) As such, I copy elements before I perform these operations. This results in a file that looks like a step-by-step assembly diagram of the object. Miss a dimension halfway through the process? No problem - adjust the appropriate element and carry it through the steps to get your re-designed object!

At some point I may include my 123D Design model for reference so you can see this process, though I'm somewhat embarrassed to show my messy workspace! :-)

Thank you for your interest in the rework of the original D Bot, The Z-Bot.

The Z-Bot is, for the most part, the same as the D-Bot. I changed all the axis to a 3-Wheel system, added a second rail for bed support.

About 2 weeks before I uploaded this, I started designing a 3 wheel carriage for my D-Bot printer. After having to recreate many parts in CAD to facilitate this design, I decided to recreate all parts from the original D-Bot, along with several different parts that I use on my printer.

In the Zip file you will find 3 folders. One has all of the original .stl files that the parts in the 4 wheel folder were made from. The 4 wheel folder has all of the parts for the original D-Bot in .stl, .step, and .sldprt formats.

In the 3 Wheel folder are all of the parts needed to make it. Most of them are the same but some of them are very different. Pay special attention to the leading numbers as this is how many are needed to produce the Z-Bot. All build instructions are the same as the D-Bot, except for the build bed. I don't like the idea of a cantilevered bed and had a lot of problems with the far edge wobbling on me so I added guides to that side as well. You will need another piece of V-Slot rail at 448mm. Install it, just like the opposing side. Once installed on the frame, make sure it slide all the way without resistance. If there is any resistance, loosen the bolts for the motor mounts or idlers on both sides and continue, once you have free range of motion with the build bed, the bolts can be retightened. This is the best way that I have found to make sure that your frame is square to the bed.

The two files in the main folder at included in the zip file. These parts were the inspiration for the build, so I figured I might as well add them.

A group of scientists have successfully frozen sperm from 16 different coral species, using liquid nitrogen. The process is called cryopreservation and the purpose is to “save” the species before they go extinct. This is a project by Marcus Nystrand at Beckmans College of Design. These 16 coral species were 3D-modeled, printed and placed in a physical interpretation of the cryohabitat, for an exhibition at Svenskt Tenn in Stockholm. description.text:
Silence, a book to be read with the senses
Silence is a collection of poems by way of micro-stories that relate feelings and sensory experiences, in many synesthetic occasions. It is independent sentences, but also as a whole short story.
This book of poetry illustrated relief to read and play for both sighted and blind people, offering a new tactile communication for all.
The book has a cover, back cover and sheet loans, inside cover, 14 pages each with poetry represented in the two alphabets, 14 pages of illustrations and description in Braille just below these for facilitars your understanding.

Feel free to contact me on the website :)

http://www.tactilebook.com/index_english.html

Printer:

Witbox 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

The height of layer used was 0.2 for the pages to not have a thickness too high and the printing time is reduced. Printing temperature used was 235 degrees knowing that it obscile between 230-240 (since it is not stable) in order to create a homogeneous surface. Retractions should be as fast and far as possible to not waste that does not generate unwanted.

http://www.tactilebook.com/print_your_book.html

Binding

Each page has a bridge and 5 holes. High bridge allows to fold the pages providing greater flexibility.

The binding was intended to facilitate the DIY (do it yourself). This binding based enquadernadors is accessible anywhere in the world and also economic. In addition the page layout opens the door to multiple possible bindings.

http://www.tactilebook.com/about_the_book.html

The material

The material with which the book is printed is flexible filament, it's very elastic and comfortable to the touch.

The page dimensions are relative to the size of the medium area of the current 3D printers.

For this project, I have been fortunate to have the help of the organization ONCE (National Organization of Spanish Blind), where I have been advised about braille, I could answer questions, testing the book and validate successfully meeting the requirements to be read by blind people.

http://www.tactilebook.com/how_it_was_made.html

Special thanks to ONCE, Néstor y Paula :)

This Thing contains the configuration files for Simplify 3D users who want to use it with their HyperCube or CoreXY printers. I was forced to have at least one STL file so I found a little frog like the one S3D uses for their website. (You may ignore it.)

I use Simplify 3D as my slicer and to control my HyperCube printer. Attached are my Factory File and my FFF Printer File for the HyperCube. They aren't perfect but they are a good starting point for the HypeCube Printer. I've also included my Marlin Configuration.h file.

You may load the Factory file directly. Import the FFF which describes the printer parameters. . If you make changes to the Factory file, you may save it on your disc. To save a FFF file you must export it.

Be sure to enter the correct build size for your printer and check parameters like the extruder nozzle size and desired temperatures. The start script homes the printer and then extrudes a 40 mm bead in the front left corner to prime the filament flow. You can easily change this script to suit your needs. I have also included an end script. If you find things I could have done better, let me know and I'll fix them and keep this "thing" updated with the best and latest.

Update 2/8/2017: I was having problems with the prime of the extruder in the start script. The extruder was sometimes moving backwards. I added a zero position of the extruder and that fixed it. The start includes a short extrude in the front left corner to prime the extruder before printing.

Update 4/7/2017: I added my HyperCube Marlin V1.1 RC8 Configuration.h Be sure to check it for compatibility before using it. I'm running with an MKS Gen V1.4 controller.

description.text:
Center skid plate for the Axial SCX10 RC crawler. This gives you a little more ground clearance to prevent getting hung up. This skid plate DOES affect link geometry slightly.

There are 2 version, once for the stock links using Axial brand ball ends, and one for the popular Traxxas Revo rod ends. The axial balls are a little wider than Revo balls, that's the only difference. If you print the revo ball version, axial rod ends won't fit.

You will also need long M3 grub screws for the lower links on the skid plate. I would say at LEAST 18mm long, so M3x18. But I would recommend even longer. M3x20 to M3x26 would work great. This will ensure enough strength on both ends. Upper link hardware should stay the same, as well as mounting the skid itself.

Photos attached are printed in Taulman3D Alloy 910 and I'm sure it will hold up great. I think ABS or PETG would work well too. I would stay away from PLA unless you are gentle on your rigs.

NOTE:
User dcfox brings up a good point in the comments:
"...but anyone who is going to use this should be aware...that it's going to shorten your wheelbase by about 5/8"...because it moves the lower link mounts upward. You'll need to build new lower links to get the wheelbase back where it belongs."

description.text:
This is a magnetic webcam boom I made for my C270 webcam. It is based on two mounts listed in the references.

I redesigned this mount to use a piece of 4mm aluminum rod or carbon fiber to help with drooping. It uses a clamp so the moving portion has friction with the clamp but the bolt and nut don't move. I also added a counter balance for the camera. If I didn't, the camera would eventually rotate as the set screw will not be able to hold that much twisting force.

I updated the Mount to use 4mm rods. and added a knuckle in the middle of the rod.

The magnets are 12mm x 3mm. I picked them up at my local hardware store. You will also need :
(3) M3x6 cap screws
(2) M3 x15 plus M3 Lock nuts
(1) M3 x12 cap crew and lock nut
(1) 4mm x 200mm of carbon fiber rod or aluminum rod
(1) 4mm x 100mm of carbon fiber rod or aluminum rod

description.text:
This thing was made with Tinkercad and is a submission to Pinshape for their call for useful things astronauts can 3D print in space.

It is a human powered personal blower for moving air comfort. Additionally, if made full size (100 mm) the device will give you a workout. Try different positions, maybe customize handles, etc to keep muscles from atrophy.

All sorts of muscle group combinations can be exercised. Certainly major limbs in multiple directions, as well as hands and fingers.

Watch a half size one in action: https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B923oYusoMRGdUVCY24zdmkzVU0/view?usp=sharing

It's also a great fidget target.

A raft is useful when on an unheated bed. No supports necessary if your machine demonstrates reasonable bridging capability.

Assembly is pretty easy. Tie a comfortable size loop of braided string/cord along with any handle you might want. With the loop untwisted, I find it easiest to 'crank' one side up, twisting the string, thereby winding up the blower. Then, with practiced timing, tug to unwind, stopping before it is unwound so it can continue and wind up the other direction...and so forth. Have fun!
